snippet.textDisplay:
Just wish I knew this side of Kobe while he was playing, it is sad we (a lot of people) have to learn about people, their whole -selves only when they pass away. I never knew it to its full extent, but what an incredible human being. That day I was thinking to myself, "only the good die young?" I was just contemplating "why kobe?"I was thinking how great he was at basketball. Yah, I am sure he helped people out on the court. But surely, if this is true, that only the good die young, that gods focus is far, far beyond basketball and far beyond your average spirit of giving..

Over the last week, I have been reminded, over and over and over and over again that indeed "only the good die young.' Kobe was an amazing human being. I never knew how kind spirited he was. How grateful he was. How genuine and real he was. How genuinely nice he was. We sure lost a great one. Somebody who may have eclipsed everybody with their impact on the league in its entirety. And the truly sad part is that he was set on making his second half even better. We all know he would have succeeded in this. Still can't believe he isnt here with us and that he wont have that chance.

snippet.textDisplay:
Guys like a Ron Artest losing a Kobe Bryant is very similar to Tyson when he lost Cus D'Amato.

The level of mentorship Ron took from KB is invaluable.

I grew up without a father myself and at 36 my son is almost 4. When you live vicariously through you children you realize how valuable you truly are to them.

Ron is a legit Queensbridge avage, Kobe fathered him and taught him how to catch a fish so too speak, bc of that he'll never be morally poor for as long as he lives.

We've all been cheated by this tragedy, as a people. To say anything less is disdainful.

Pay the Mamba Mentality forward to your children and all people.

snippet.textDisplay: It’s so true what he said...” who knows what else it’s affecting” Who would think it’s affecting me... a 52 years young woman, not really a huge Basketball fan... but this isn’t really a basketball story. It’s a human story. On one hand I’ve been so very sad for the 4 days since the accident. Just hurting so much for his wife and daughters, for all the basketball players and coaches I’ve seen cry... for the loss of such a bright light and his mini bright light, Gianna. And on the other hand I’ve become so incredibly inspired by everything I’m learning about him and all he’s done, and has continued to do after retirement. I’ve been at a cross roads and hearing about the mamba mentality has really helped me. And it’s always nice to see so much love happening.
